      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Camping has become exceptionally popular but most campers constrain themselves to the summer months. With the right <a title="camping equipment" href="http://www.raymears.com/">camping equipment</a> and <a title="Outdoor Clothing" href="http://www.raymears.com/Bushcraft_Products/Outdoor_Clothing/">outdoor clothing</a> camping can be enjoyed at any time of year.</p>
<p> There are many benefits to camping outside the peak summer months. There are no summer crowds and the campsites are empty, the winter countryside presents some fantastic views and you&#8217;ll not have to contend with annoying insects.</p>
<p> It really is all about being prepared. The sometimes freezing winter weather can be the most challenging aspect of camping out at this time of year. Temperatures that fall below freezing at night are enough to put many people off sleeping out in a sleeping bag. But with a good quality sleeping bag and the right thermal insulation you&#8217;ll not have any problems.</p>
<p> I am, of course, talking about sleeping out in a tent or if you&#8217;re really brave a tarpaulin. The other option is to use a camper-van or motor-home. These enable you to bring a whole range of home comforts including heating.</p>
<p> But for a &#8216;real&#8217; winter camping experience I strongly recommend using a tent, a camping bed or airbed to insulate you from the cold hard ground, a really good sleeping bag and some top quality thermal underwear. Equip yourself with good quality outdoor clothing that is waterproof, windproof, lightweight but ventilated along with gloves, boots and a hat and you should not have any problems whatever the weather.</p>
<p> Camping in the summer months is a lot of fun but nothing like the challenge presented by sub-zero winter camping. Warming yourself by a blazing camp fire is much more appreciated when there is frost on the ground and the possibility of snow and walks in the countryside on crisp, clear winter days can be exceptionally rewarding.</p>
<p> So, if you like a little adventure, or maybe you are looking for something to do with your family during the Christmas break, why not spend a couple of nights under canvas and enjoy the challenge of a little winter camping.</p>
